    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-01-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-01-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="313"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d313">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6131/377</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SFB1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sayre</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-14">January 14,
                            1936</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Bullitt</persName>, in the course of a
                    conversation concerning the situation in Russia, spoke, among other subjects, of
                    the trade situation. He adverted to the agreement entered into last June [<hi
                        rend="italic">July</hi>] under which the United States agreed to extend to
                    Russia most-favored-nation treatment in return for an agreement by Russia to
                    increase its purchase of American goods so as not to fall below a certain
                    amount. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">Bullitt</persName> said that he felt
                    confident that Russia is in a position to buy large quantities of American
                    goods. Russia lacks and needs American goods. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BWC1"
                        >Bullitt</persName> gave it as his opinion that if the present agreement
                    should be renewed for another year Russia should be asked <pb facs="0429"
                        n="323" xml:id="pg_323"/> to increase substantially the amount of American
                    goods to be bought by her. He suggested that in his opinion we should ask Russia
                    to buy a minimum of $50,000,000 worth of American goods for the year.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SFB1">F[<hi rend="smallcaps">rancis</hi>] B. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">Sayre</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
